      In the age when the gods still walked among mortals, there lived a host named **Haldor**, keeper of the last inn along the **Blackthorn Pass**. His hearth was sacred, for it stood beneath the **Oak of the Traveler**, a tree planted by the god **Veythar** himself, who decreed: *'No guest shall leave my door unfed, nor my roof unprotected—lest the hearth’s fire gutter out and the house fall to ruin.'*

      One winter, a traveler arrived at dusk, cloaked in tattered furs, their face hidden by a hood. They spoke in riddles, and their hands bore strange scars—some said they were a **banished spirit**, others a **thief in disguise**. Haldor, bound by the **Law of the Hearth**, offered them bread, mead, and a place by the fire. *'Guest-right is older than kings,'* he told his wary wife. *'To break it is to invite the wrath of the unseen.'*

      That night, a band of outlaws stormed the inn, demanding the traveler be handed over—*'That one owes us blood,'* their leader snarled. When Haldor refused, they set torch to the thatch. The traveler, revealing themselves as **Veythar in mortal guise**, raised a hand—and the flames turned to ice. The outlaws fled, but the inn lay in ruins.

      As dawn broke, the god restored the hearth. *'You honored the sacred law,'* Veythar said. *'Hospitality is not kindness—it is the **first covenant**, the thread that binds the living to the divine. To violate it is to unweave the world.'* From that day, the **Oath of the Hearth-Fire** was carved into every doorpost: *'No guest shall be turned away, no host shall be harmed for their mercy—lest the gods remember, and the unbroken chain be broken.'*
    "
  }
}
```

